  "prompt": "Is O-ve universal donor?",
  "response": "Yes, **O-negative (O\u207b) blood is considered the universal donor for red blood cell transfusions**. Here's why:\n\n### Why O-Negative is the Universal Red Blood Cell Donor\n\n1. **Lack of A and B Antigens**: O-negative blood does not have A or B antigens on the surface of its red blood cells. This means it can be safely transfused to individuals of any ABO blood type (A, B, AB, or O) without the risk of an immune reaction against these antigens.\n\n2. **Absence of Rh Factor**: Being Rh-negative means O-negative blood lacks the Rh (Rhesus) antigen. This is crucial because Rh-negative individuals can develop antibodies against Rh-positive blood if exposed to it. By using O-negative blood, healthcare providers avoid complications related to Rh incompatibility.\n\n### When O-Negative Blood is Used\n\n- **Emergency Situations**: In emergencies where there's no time to determine the patient's blood type, O-negative blood is often used because it's less likely to cause adverse reactions.\n- **Neonates and Certain Medical Conditions**: Some newborns, especially those with Rh-negative blood, and patients with specific medical conditions may require O-negative blood.\n\n### Limitations\n\n- **Supply Constraints**: O-negative blood is relatively rare (found in about 7% of the population), making it a limited resource in blood banks.\n- **Not Universal for Plasma or Platelets**: While O-negative is universal for red blood cells, it's not universal for plasma or platelet transfusions. For plasma transfusions, **AB blood type** is considered the universal donor because AB plasma lacks anti-A and anti-B antibodies.\n\n### Summary\n\n- **Universal Donor for Red Blood Cells**: O-negative is the go-to choice.\n- **Universal Donor for Plasma**: AB blood type is preferred.\n  \nIt's important to use the appropriate blood type based on the specific needs of the transfusion to ensure safety and compatibility.",
